Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have compared the earthquake, tsunami, and Japanese nuclear disaster to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The resemblance is quite clear: both activities generate large profits and involve a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crises ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with normally harmless design flaws, caused the shutdown of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
In the case of financial markets, an unexpected collapse of housing values, combined with design flaws in derivative and mortgage markets, damaged the ability of important financial institutions to honor their debts.
While basic risks arise outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, overinvestment in mortgage-backed securities for financial institutions – design defects and a lack of fortitude ensured that the systems could not contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or mortgages – went bankrupt, causing a freeze on credit in the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand fairly well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
We cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives that shook the global economy.
At Fukushima, workers are bravely trying to stop the radiation leaks.
However, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not prevent the next financial crisis.
We are recreating similar derivatives and financial structures over the same errors that remain active.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for example, one party takes on the risk of euro fluctuations but does not want yen risk, while another party will take the opposite view.
In this case, the first party promises to provide euros on June 1st, and the second party promises to provide yen.
If one currency loses value against another, the loser pays the difference.
Repurchase agreements are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bonds or mortgage debts, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the term "repo," which is short for the English verb repurchase – or buy back, n.d.).
The problem is that the cash from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheet of the most important financial institutions, meaning that simple financial tremors can significantly impact them.
Some institutions may then find themselves unable to obtain repo financing, as happened in 2008, and go bankrupt, like Bear Stearns.
Individual derivative or repurchase agreement transactions are not particularly blamable.
Each separately transfers risk legitimately to those better able to bear it, or allows financial participation.
However, when used excessively by systemically vital institutions, they can blow up the financial system due to its design flaws.
Today, about 70% of the assets of major American financial firms consist of very short-term loans, such as overnight repos.
In the US, the main design flaws are found in bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual bankruptcy constraints.
For example, investors holding derivative or repo contracts with financially weakened institutions can seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its normal creditors. In doing so, they can decide its fate when, with a bit more time, the company in question could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos find themselves at the front of the line for repayment in so many ways, they have fewer incentives to encourage market discipline by closely checking the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid anyway.
Of course, someone has to be first.
Other financial actors bear more risk because the exemptions for derivatives and repo players place them at the forefront in case of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect that other actors would therefore have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor next in line is often the American government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (too important to fail, n.d.). Yet, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often confines itself to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The U.S. Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major overhaul of finance it adopted last summer through the Dodd-Frank bill.
But he did not seize it.
If investors in derivatives, including credit-default swaps (credit event derivatives, n.d.), were not given preferential treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would insist more often that their counterparties be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk associated with ultra-low capitalizations when it was essentially American government money; they would be less likely to do so if it were their own money at stake.
The public perceives the risks of Fukushima differently from the risks associated with derivatives.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking, causing sectors facing security concerns to slow down.
But derivatives and repo markets present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in media, and complicated for politicians to debate and resolve.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and scrutiny but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding Fukushima-type risks, analysts are already discussing how nuclear plants can be designed and built to contain earthquake and tsunami-related risks through passive cooling systems.
It is now considered possible to design nuclear plants that can keep fuel rods cool even in total loss of electrical power.
On the other hand, little significant progress has been made so far to prevent the damage that the priority of derivatives and repos in case of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require that final users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect against unexpected changes in oil prices) and others post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main issue: the weak market discipline incentives for the major financial institutions.
It is as if we were reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully make investors in derivatives and repos bear the risk associated with their decisions when they transact with financial institutions that are systemic in nature.
Instead, we survived the financial tsunami of 2008 only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
